# GitHub Workflow

## Use GitHub MCP

When interacting with GitHub (issues, pull requests, labels, repo metadata), **always use the GitHub MCP** (`user-github` server). Do not use the `gh` CLI unless MCP is unavailable or the user explicitly requests the CLI.

Before calling an MCP tool, read its schema descriptor under `mcps/user-github/tools/`.

## Pull requests must close the task issue

Every PR must link to the corresponding GitHub issue so it **auto-closes on merge**. Include one of these keywords in the PR body:

```
Closes #N
```

Use the issue number from the repo (search by title `TASK-XX:` if needed). Issue mapping for early tasks:

| Task | Issue |
|------|-------|
| TASK-01 | #3 |
| TASK-02 | #2 |
| TASK-03 | #1 |
| TASK-04 … TASK-33 | same number as task (e.g. TASK-05 → #5) |

PR title format: `TASK-XX: <short summary>`.

## Pull requests must include a test plan

Every PR body must include a **## Test plan** section describing how changes were verified. Use checkboxes:

```markdown
## Test plan

- [x] Step taken to verify (command run, manual check, etc.)
- [ ] Step not yet verified (only if blocked; explain why)
```

Run relevant commands when possible (build, tests, manual smoke test) and record what was actually executed—not generic placeholders.

## PR body template

```markdown
## Summary

- Bullet summary of changes

## Task

Implements [#N — TASK-XX: …](https://github.com/Eaglegor/GaragePlaymate/issues/N).

Closes #N

## Test plan

- [x] ...
```
